Missed reproductive events can reduce accuracy of uncertainty estimates in matrix population models

Emily Simmonds

2023-03-17

Introduction

  • Imperfect data are common place in ecological studies. Difficulties in measuring all individuals in a population, coupled with the cryptic nature of many wild organisms mean that we often cannot fully observe particular processes occurring in natural populations. As a result, there is an observation process present in our data and an imperfect mapping from the population of interest to our samples. Such data must be dealt with appropriately in statistical models to prevent the addition of unaccounted for uncertainty into ecological results.

  • To deal with imperfect data correctly we need models that not only capture the biological process of interest but also the observation process that gave rise to our observed data (CITE). With recent increases in computational power and ease of fitting more complex models on ordinary laptops (CITE), it is now accessible to construct and fit such models more easily. Indeed, the use of these so called state-space models in ecological studies is getting more common (CITE), but far from ubiquitous.

  • Matrix population models (MPMs) are widely applied ecological tools used to predict population changes and understand various aspects of species life histories. The data that are the basis of these MPMs are subject to many of the difficulties typical of ecological data; being often a small subset of the total population and imperfectly observed, especially for elusive or cryptic species. Therefore, the statistical models or calculations that estimate the vital rates that are the parameters of these models should include explicit observation processes.

  • While we have a comprehensive and widely applied set of tools for account for the observation processes in our survival data (MARK, E-SURGE etc), the same sophisticated methods are rarely used for data on reproductive success. We found in a review of published MPMs that only X% of papers modelled an explicit observation process for reproductive parameters, in contrast to X% for survival parameters.

  • Therefore, observation errors in reproductive success are likely going unaccounted for in many of our studies. Given that reproductive events can be especially hard to identify for many species causing missed individuals and are often based on small sample sizes or subject to count errors (CITE) this could be a problem for the inference we draw from analyses using these estimates. But how much impact would these ignored observation processes actually have on derived estimates (such as population growth rate) from MPMs?

  • In this study we explore the potential consequences of the omission of explicit modelling of an observation process under five scenarios of reproductive data error and bias; perfect observation, count error, missing individuals at random, bias to missing first time breeders, bias to missing experienced breeders. All scenarios have imperfect observation of survival. We explore the impact of ignoring these errors and bias on the accuracy, precision, and precision accuracy (coverage) of estimates of the population growth rate for three matrix sizes and covering a range of different life histories.

Method

  • First I selected 2x2 matrices from COMADRE (published since 2010 and in peer reviewed literature). I reduced these to only matrices where both stage classes breed. I then organised these based on the sum of their fecundity values. This gave 10 matrices, so I selected every other matrix from the lowest fecundity value to the second highest. This gave a range of different levels of fecundity.

  • Next I expanded these five 2x2 matrices to 3x3 and 5x5.

  • I did this by repeating the survival and fecundity values with some tweaks. First, the number of breeding stages varied by matrix size and was 2 for 3x3 and 4 for 5x5. Earliest breeding stage has earliest breeding stage fecundity from 2x2 matrix, all others have repeat of adult stage fecundity. Youngest stage has youngest stage survival from 2x2, all others repeated.

  • Stable lambda (>1 < 1.2) was needed for simulations, so if expanded matrix had lambda < 1 all matrix elements were increased by 10%.

  • Once matrices were established, recapture data was simulated with recapture rate of 1 for first year individuals and 0.8 thereafter.

  • Five scenarios were used

    1. Baseline: this has imperfect detection of survival but no error in fecundity.

    2. Random error: this has imperfect detection of survival and random count error in fecundity - universal across all breeding groups.

    3. Random missing: this has imperfect detection of survival and imperfect detection of breeding events. The missing breeding events occur at random (10%).

    4. Missing first time breeders: this has imperfect detection of survival and imperfect detection of breeding events for first time breeders (20% missing).

    5. Missing post-first time breeders: this has imperfect detection of survival and imperfect detection of breeding events for post-first time breeders (20% missing).

  • I then ran a Bayesian model with a hidden markov multistate model for survival and Poisson regression for fecundity - no observation error modelled for fecundity.

Results: Accuracy

Accuracy metric: error i.e.difference between estimate and true value.

Accuracy - by scenario and matrix size

Accuracy organised by scenario and matrix size (2x2, 3x3, 5x5).

Interpretation: matrix size has little impact on results, maybe slightly less impact of bias in the larger matrix (higher role of survival).

Accuracy - by scenario and fecundity importance

Accuracy organised by scenario and fecundity importance (1 = lowest, 5 = highest).

Just presented for 2x2 matrices.

Interpretation: Variability of error differs by matrix. Generally, there is more error in random error scenario but this is normally distributed. Can see most bias to estimate with random missing scenario and least for juvenile missing.

Results: Precision

Precision is measured by credible interval width.

Precision - across all combos

Results shown for all matrices as all results are very similar. Little changes CI width.

Results: Coverage (accuracy of precision)

Coverage is the number of times the true parameter falls in the 95% credible interval. Would expect it to be 95% but this is not always the case.

This gives a measure of how accurate our precision metric is.

Coverage - lambda by scenario

Coverage of lambda plotted with mean % for each scenario across all matrix sizes and fecundity importance.

## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'scenario'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Interpretation: On average, coverage is highest in the baseline scenario but still not 95% expected. This is because recapture rate and consequently survival are hard to estimate in this example due to low survival and high recapture. Random error has little impact on coverage but all bias scenarios have a big impact. For this, the uncertainty estimated is way off.

Coverage - lambda by matrix size

Coverage of lambda plotted as mean % for matrix size across all fecundity levels.

## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'matrix_size'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Interpretation: As this is across all scenarios, the average % drops a lot. But is lowest for 3x3 matrices.

Coverage - lambda by fecundity ratio

Coverage of lambda plotted for 2x2 matrices only and facetted by fecundity importance (1 = lowest, 5 = highest).

Interpretation: Coverage close to 95% for baseline but drops for all error and bias scenarios. Suggests that uncertainty incorrectly estimated if we have unaccounted for bias and error, especially randomly missing individuals.

Results: Comparison with direct estimation method

I also ran all scenarios through a model that directly estimates vital rates and then adds uncertainty through bootstrap. This more directly follows Caswells book but does not account for imperfect detection in survival.

General patterns = more error, wider confidence intervals but worse coverage.

As expected - just a sense check.
